        <body>
            <div type="emblem" n="e15"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="50"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Epigramme</orig> 15. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>Let the <orig>worke</orig> of the Potter, consisting in siccity and moisture,
                        <lb/>instruct you.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 15.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Water the Potter mixing with his clay,</l>
                        <l>Makes <orig>vessells</orig> <choice><orig>Shapd</orig><reg>Shaped</reg></choice> by <choice><orig>wheele</orig></choice> without delay:</l>
                        <l>This <orig>cheifely</orig> <orig>dos</orig> his <choice><orig>aime</orig><reg>aim</reg></choice> and art <choice><orig>expresse</orig><reg>express</reg></choice>,</l>
                        <l>The thirsty earth with liquor to refresh:</l>
                        <l>His road is safe, proceed, and <orig>doe</orig> not <choice><orig>turne</orig><reg>turn</reg></choice></l>
                        <l><choice><orig>Drowne</orig><reg>Drowne</reg></choice> not your earth, nor suffer it to <orig>burne</orig>.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="51"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 15.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>As this <orig>orbe</orig> is by the <choice><orig>connexion</orig><reg>connection</reg></choice> of earth and water conglobated into one<milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>round body, <orig>soe</orig> <orig>allso</orig> the Potters <orig>worke</orig> seems to be compounded of the
                        <lb/>same Elements particularly, namely of siccity and moisture, that one
                        <lb/>may regulate the other: for if the earth should be without water, nei
                        <lb break="no"/>ther the Ocean, sea, lakes, rivers, or fountains would be near the earth,
                        <lb/>it could bear nothing of <orig>itselfe</orig>, but <orig>remaine</orig> barren: <orig>Soe</orig> if water should
                        <lb/>not be received into the <choice><orig>cavityes</orig><reg>cavities</reg></choice> of the earth, but stand about, it would
                        <lb/>easily cover the whole earth, and <orig>soe</orig> the same <orig>remayne</orig> inhabitable:
                        <lb/>but one <choice><orig>entring</orig><reg>entering</reg></choice> amicably into the other, and water moderating the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>siccity of the earth, the earth the moisture of that, by their <orig>mutuall</orig>
                        <lb/><choice><orig>comixtion</orig><reg>commixtion</reg></choice>, hereby is the fertility and utility of both Elements conspi
                        <lb break="no"/>cuous: In like manner the Potter <choice><orig>mixeth</orig><reg>mixes</reg></choice> clay with water, to make<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>thereof a tractable <orig>masse</orig>, which <orig>hee</orig> Shapes by his <orig>wheele</orig>, and <choice><orig>setts</orig><reg>sets</reg></choice> in
                        <lb/>the warme <orig>aire</orig>, that it may be gradually <choice><orig>dryed</orig><reg>dried</reg></choice>; then adds violence of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>fire, that his <orig>vessells</orig> may be well hardened, and condensed into a durable
                        <lb/>stone, which can resist both water and fire: <orig>Soe</orig> <orig>allso</orig> must <orig>wee</orig> proceed
                        <lb/>in the <orig>naturall</orig> <orig>worke</orig> as the Philosophers attest, and therefore <orig>doe</orig> <orig>affirme</orig>
                        <lb/>that example ought to be taken from the potters. For as to siccity and<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>moisture, that is, earth and water, <orig>wee</orig> doubt not that there is much<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>affinity in both, but much difference in the way of coction, and in the
                        <lb/>matter and <orig>forme</orig> of compounding the Elements: For Potters <orig>vessells</orig> have
                        <lb/>an <orig>artificiall</orig> <orig>forme</orig>, the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> tincture a <orig>forme</orig> <orig>alltogether</orig> <orig>natu
                        <lb break="no"/>rall</orig>, and <orig>soe</orig> much more noble than they, by how much the more excel
                        <lb break="no"/>lent the matter of this is than theirs: either is indeed a <orig>worke</orig> of earth, but
                        <lb/>in the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> there is nothing <orig>sayd</orig> to be, which <orig>hath</orig> not ascended
                        <lb/>and attained to the heaven of <orig>aire</orig>, in that a <orig>thicke</orig> and <choice><orig>fæculent</orig><reg>feculent</reg></choice> earth is
                        <lb/><choice><orig>prædominant</orig><reg>predominant</reg></choice>: The effect of both is a stone, there a <orig>comon</orig>, here a <orig>Philo
                        <lb break="no"/>sophicall</orig>: by which name a <orig>certaine</orig> person being seduced put a great<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>number of <orig>artificiall</orig> stones or <choice><orig>tyles</orig><reg>tiles</reg></choice> into one chest, and the whiter sort
                        <lb/>of flints into another, using <choice><orig>Diabolicall</orig><reg>Diabolical</reg></choice> conjurations from above, by
                        <lb/>which the last were at a <orig>certaine</orig> time to be converted into silver, the
                        <lb/>first into pure gold: but they being supposed to be the Philosophers
                        <lb/>Stones, and therefore a great <choice><orig>summe</orig><reg>sum</reg></choice> of <choice><orig>mony</orig><reg>money</reg></choice> <choice><orig>accrewing</orig><reg>accruing</reg></choice> to purchase <orig>se
                        <lb/>verall</orig> things, when the new gold and Silver might be expected, at a
                        <lb/><orig>certaine</orig> time, in which it not appearing, nor the stones converted into
                        <lb/>gold, as was desired, death put an end to the folly and Shame: For gold
                        <lb/>or Silver ought not to be expected from that thing, in which it is not na
                        <lb break="no"/>turally, <orig>diabolicall</orig> <choice><orig>Magicke</orig><reg>Magic</reg></choice> having <orig>noe</orig> place in these divine works, but
                        <lb/>is as <orig>farre</orig> different from them, as the author of it from a devout and<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>pious man, hell from heaven: <orig>Soe</orig> though it may be esteemed the true
                        <lb/><orig>Philosophicall</orig> stone, yet let not any man <choice><orig>perswade</orig><reg>persuade</reg></choice> <orig>himselfe</orig>, that im
                        <lb break="no"/>possible things can performed by it, us <choice><orig>Isaack</orig><reg>Isaac</reg></choice> <choice><orig>admonisheth</orig><reg>admonishes</reg></choice>: <orig>noe</orig> man
                        <lb/>being bound either by the <orig>lawes</orig> of nature, or polity to things im
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="52"/><fw>Discourse 15.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb break="no"/>possible: as for the transmutation of <choice><orig>gemms</orig><reg>gems</reg></choice> by it, and performing the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>malleability of <orig>glasse</orig> any man thereby perceive, whether these
                        <lb/>things are possible, and congrous to this nature, or <orig>noe</orig>: Geber affirms<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>that the Philosophers <orig>speake</orig> many things allegorically, as <orig>allso</orig> of <orig>him
                        <lb break="no"/>selfe</orig>, that where <orig>hee</orig> Spoke clearly and plainly, <orig>hee</orig> <orig>sayd</orig> nothing, but<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>where figuratively, there <orig>hee</orig> absconded the truth, as wheat under<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><choice><orig>chaffe</orig><reg>chaff</reg></choice>: Those things which a man <choice><orig>sowes</orig><reg>sows</reg></choice>, the same <orig>allso</orig> will <orig>hee</orig> reap, which takes
                        <lb/>place in vegetables and <orig>animalls</orig>, though different Species may sometimes proceed
                        <lb/>from the things sowed: whether these ought to be <choice><orig>applyed</orig><reg>applied</reg></choice> to <orig>metalls</orig>,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which are not propagated by seed, as those, must be considered: In these the
                        <lb/>parts <orig>onely</orig> are homogeneous, Sulphur, and Argent vive, in those they are hete
                        <lb break="no"/>rogeneous or <choice><orig>organicke</orig><reg>organic</reg></choice>: In these are <orig>noe</orig> receptacles of seed, but in those:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>In these there is not found any nutrition, augmentation, or extension in all
                        <lb/>dimensions, in those very much: yea these are elemented weights admitting
                        <lb/>mixtion alone, those <orig>allso</orig> besides mixtion have either a vegetine or sensitive
                        <lb/><orig>soule</orig>: <orig>Neverthelesse</orig> it is without doubt true that there is something in places
                        <lb/>under the earth, which is not gold now, but will after a thousand years be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>gold by nature: Who will deny this to be the <choice><orig>analogicall</orig><reg>analogical</reg></choice> seed of gold? both<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>gold and the <choice><orig>aurificke</orig><reg>aurific</reg></choice> nature being of one <orig>originall</orig> and radix, though<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>this of the more noble <orig>forme</orig>, and therefore the seed of gold being <orig>knowne</orig>,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>this <orig>allso</orig> will be manifested: The Philosophers <orig>affirme</orig> siccity and mois
                        <lb break="no"/>ture or Sulphur and Argent vive to be that, which being most pure must
                        <lb/>be extracted out of two mountains<pc>. . . . . . . . . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
            </div>
